  "text": "A large set of human genomic data was analyzed to quantify the penetrance of variants of the human PrP C gene (PRNP) in prion disease [CITATION_1] . Surprisingly, heterozygous loss-of-function variants were identified in three individuals. These individuals in their 50s and 70s are probably healthy, and no evidence of any neurological defect or peripheral neuropathy was documented. This result suggests that heterozygous loss of PRNP in humans may not be haploinsufficient. It remains to be assessed, however, whether homozygous deletion and therefore complete loss of PrP C may create a disease in humans.",
